Based on my search, here's information about Premiere Pro's `insertClip`, `overwriteClip`, and sequence automation scripting:

## Premiere Pro Sequence Scripting Methods

### insertClip()
The `insertClip` method inserts a clip into the sequence, on the specified video and audio tracks, at the specified time.(no content)Returns a boolean; true if successful.

**Syntax:**
```javascript
app.project.sequences[index].insertClip(projectItem, time, vTrackIndex, aTrackIndex)
```

This can also be accomplished through `app.project.activeSequence.videoTracks[x].insertClip(clip, timecode in seconds)`.

### overwriteClip()
`overwriteClip` inserts a clip into the sequence, overwriting existing clips, on the specified video and audio tracks, at the specified time.(no content)Overwriting will not shift anything around, it will just place it on top and delete whatever was there before it. If you would like to place the clip at the current player position, you can use `var playerPosition = app.project.activeSequence.getPlayerPosition(); app.project.activeSequence.videoTracks[x].overwriteClip(clip, playerPosition.seconds)`.

### Example Code from Adobe's Official Sample

From Adobe's official PProPanel sample: `var newClip = seq.insertClip(first, time, (seq.videoTracks.numTracks - 1), (seq.audioTracks.numTracks - 1));`

### Nesting Sequence Example

While the Premiere Pro scripting API does not natively offer a "nest" function, you can still use ExtendScript to accomplish this task by writing your own function using the `createSubsequence()` method to mimic the nest functionality.

Here's a function example for nesting:
```javascript
function nestSelection() {
    var activeSequence = app.project.activeSequence;
    var selection = activeSequence.getSelection();
    if (!selection.length) { return; }
    var trackId = selection[0].parentTrackIndex;
    var start = selection[0].start;
    var end = selection[selection.length - 1].end;
    activeSequence.setInPoint(start.seconds);
    activeSequence.setOutPoint(end.seconds);
    var nestedSequence = activeSequence.createSubsequence(true);
    activeSequence.videoTracks[trackId].overwriteClip(nestedSequence.projectItem, start.seconds);
    return nestedSequence;
}
```

### Important Notes

Editing to a Sequence time code of type number (seconds) works as expected.(no content)However, editing to a Sequence time code of type string does not seem to work as suggested - the string is interpreted as 0 seconds.(no content)It doesn't seem to matter whether you choose the target sequence's videoTracks or audioTracks. Executing insertClip/overwriteClip always carries all picture and sound tracks from source clip to sequence.(no content)However, it does matter which track layer is chosen. Choosing videoTracks[0] or audioTracks[0] means a source clip with 1 picture track and 2 sound tracks will route to V1 and A1/A2 on the record side.


